<section id="s02">
<div class="section-inner">
<div class="section-header hidden stagger-1">
<div class="section-number">02 / WAVEFORM LAB</div>
<h2>Waveform Lab</h2>
<p class="section-thesis">What a waveform is determines what a sound contains.</p>
</div>
<div class="two-panel hidden stagger-2">
<!-- LEFT: oscilloscope canvas + controls -->
<div>
<div class="canvas-wrap">
<canvas height="200" id="wl-canvas" style="width:100%;height:200px;" width="540"></canvas>
</div>
<div class="controls mt-16">
<div class="control-row">
<span class="control-label">Morph</span>
<input id="wl-morph" max="3" min="0" oninput="wlMorphChange(this.value)" step="0.01" type="range" value="0"/>
<span class="control-value" id="wl-morph-val">SINE</span>
</div>
<div class="control-row">
<span class="control-label">Frequency</span>
<input id="wl-freq" max="880" min="55" oninput="wlFreqChange(this.value)" step="1" type="range" value="220"/>
<span class="control-value" id="wl-freq-val">220 Hz</span>
</div>
<div class="control-row">
<span class="control-label">Amplitude</span>
<input id="wl-amp" max="1.0" min="0.1" oninput="wlAmpChange(this.value)" step="0.01" type="range" value="0.7"/>
<span class="control-value" id="wl-amp-val">0.70</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class="btn-row mt-16">
<button class="btn" id="wl-play-btn" onclick="wlTogglePlay()">▶ PLAY</button>
<button class="btn" id="wl-freeze-btn" onclick="wlToggleFreeze()">FREEZE</button>
</div>
</div>
<!-- RIGHT: harmonic ladder -->
<div>
<h4 style="margin-bottom:12px;">Harmonic Content</h4>
<div class="harmonic-ladder" id="harmonic-ladder">
<div class="harmonic-bar-wrap"><div class="harmonic-bar" id="hb-1" style="height:90%;"></div><div class="harmonic-label">Fund.</div></div>
<div class="harmonic-bar-wrap"><div class="harmonic-bar" id="hb-2" style="height:2px;"></div><div class="harmonic-label">2nd</div></div>
<div class="harmonic-bar-wrap"><div class="harmonic-bar" id="hb-3" style="height:2px;"></div><div class="harmonic-label">3rd</div></div>
<div class="harmonic-bar-wrap"><div class="harmonic-bar" id="hb-4" style="height:2px;"></div><div class="harmonic-label">4th</div></div>
<div class="harmonic-bar-wrap"><div class="harmonic-bar" id="hb-5" style="height:2px;"></div><div class="harmonic-label">5th</div></div>
<div class="harmonic-bar-wrap"><div class="harmonic-bar" id="hb-6" style="height:2px;"></div><div class="harmonic-label">6th</div></div>
<div class="harmonic-bar-wrap"><div class="harmonic-bar" id="hb-7" style="height:2px;"></div><div class="harmonic-label">7th</div></div>
<div class="harmonic-bar-wrap"><div class="harmonic-bar" id="hb-8" style="height:2px;"></div><div class="harmonic-label">8th</div></div>
</div>
<div class="note-text">
        The harmonic series: integer multiples of the fundamental frequency. Sine waves contain only the fundamental. Sawtooth waves contain all harmonics. Square and triangle waves contain only odd harmonics — each with its own amplitude envelope that sculpts the timbre.
      </div>
<div class="mt-16 info-text" style="font-size:13px;">
<span class="highlight">Morph slider</span> interpolates continuously:
        Sine → Triangle → Sawtooth → Square. Watch the harmonic bars fill as complex waveforms emerge from pure ones.
      </div>
</div>
</div>
<!-- PWM SECTION -->
<div class="card hidden stagger-3 mt-32">
<h3>Pulse Width Modulation</h3>
<p class="info-text" style="margin-bottom:20px;">
      A <span class="highlight">pulse wave</span> is a square wave with an adjustable duty cycle — the ratio of high time to total cycle time.
      Narrow pulses sound thin and nasal; wide pulses become full and hollow. Modulating the pulse width
      continuously creates a <span class="amber-text">chorusing, animated timbre</span> — a defining sound of classic analog synthesis,
      heard on the Roland Juno-6, Oberheim OB-Xa, and countless others.
    </p>
<div class="two-panel" style="gap:24px;">
<div>
<div class="canvas-wrap">
<canvas height="120" id="pwm-canvas" style="width:100%;height:120px;" width="500"></canvas>
</div>
<div class="control-row mt-16">
<span class="control-label">Pulse Width</span>
<input id="pwm-slider" max="90" min="10" oninput="drawPWM();document.getElementById('pwm-val').textContent=this.value+'%'" step="1" type="range" value="50"/>
<span class="control-value" id="pwm-val">50%</span>
</div>
<div class="btn-row mt-16">
<button class="btn btn-sm" id="pwm-play-btn" onclick="pwmTogglePlay()">▶ PLAY PWM</button>
<button class="btn btn-sm btn-amber" onclick="startPWMSweep()">AUTO SWEEP</button>
</div>
</div>
<div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;justify-content:center;gap:16px;">
<div>
<h4>Duty Cycle = <span id="pwm-pct" style="color:var(--amber);">50%</span></h4>
<p class="info-text" style="font-size:13px;">At 50%, the pulse wave is a perfect square wave with strong odd harmonics. As the duty cycle narrows, even harmonics re-emerge and the sound brightens. At extremes (10% or 90%), the thin pulse has a distinctive buzzy edge used in classic bass lines.</p>
</div>
<div class="note-text">
          PWM on the Minimoog: manually sweeping the pulse width while holding a note. PWM LFO on the Juno-6: automatic chorus-like shimmer without a dedicated chorus unit.
        </div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</section>
<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════
     S03  INTERFERENCE — BEATING + LISSAJOUS
═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="s03">
<div class="section-inner">
<div class="section-header hidden stagger-1">
<div class="section-number">03 / INTERFERENCE</div>
<h2>Interference</h2>
<p class="section-thesis">Two oscillators: alignment, beating, and chaos.</p>
</div>
<!-- BEATING LAB -->
<div class="card hidden stagger-2 mb-24">
<h3>Oscillator Beating Lab</h3>
<p class="info-text mb-24">When two oscillators are near but not at the same frequency, they periodically reinforce and cancel — creating a rhythmic amplitude pulse called <span class="highlight">beating</span>. The beat frequency equals the absolute difference between the two pitches.</p>
<div class="two-panel" style="gap:24px;align-items:start;">
<div>
<div class="canvas-wrap">
<canvas height="160" id="beat-canvas" style="width:100%;height:160px;" width="540"></canvas>
</div>
<div class="controls mt-16">
<div class="control-row">
<span class="control-label">Osc A (fixed)</span>
<input id="beat-freqA" max="880" min="110" oninput="beatFreqAChange(this.value)" step="1" type="range" value="440"/>
<span class="control-value" id="beat-freqA-val">440 Hz</span>
</div>
<div class="control-row">
<span class="control-label">Osc B Detune</span>
<input id="beat-detune" max="50" min="-50" oninput="beatDetuneChange(this.value)" step="0.5" type="range" value="0"/>
<span class="control-value" id="beat-detune-val">0 ¢</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class="btn-row mt-16">
<button class="btn" id="beat-play-btn" onclick="beatTogglePlay()">▶ PLAY BOTH</button>
<button class="btn btn-sm" onclick="beatDetuneChange(5);document.getElementById('beat-detune').value=5;">+5¢ DEMO</button>
<button class="btn btn-sm" onclick="beatDetuneChange(17);document.getElementById('beat-detune').value=17;">+17¢ FAST</button>
</div>
</div>
<div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;align-items:center;gap:8px;padding-top:20px;">
<div class="beat-display" id="beat-freq-display">0.0</div>
<div class="beat-label">BEATS / SECOND</div>
<div class="note-text mt-16">
          At 0–4 beats/sec: a slow, organic tremolo. At 5–15: a rough, vocal wobble. At 16–30: perceived as a low-pitched buzz. Above 30: the two tones fuse perceptually into a new timbre. This is how tuning a piano works — tighten until the beating stops.
        </div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<!-- LISSAJOUS -->
<div class="card hidden stagger-3">
<h3>Lissajous Artist</h3>
<p class="info-text mb-24">Feed two oscillators into the X and Y axes of an oscilloscope. When their frequency ratio is a simple integer, the trace locks into a stable geometric form. Fractional ratios produce slowly rotating, never-quite-repeating figures.</p>
<div class="two-panel" style="gap:32px;">
<div>
<div class="canvas-wrap" style="aspect-ratio:1;max-width:380px;">
<canvas height="380" id="liss-canvas" style="width:100%;height:100%;" width="380"></canvas>
</div>
<div style="margin-top:12px;text-align:center;">
<div style="font-family:monospace;font-size:10px;color:var(--text-dim);letter-spacing:0.15em;">
            X: <span id="liss-xf-disp" style="color:var(--green);">3</span> :
            Y: <span id="liss-yf-disp" style="color:var(--green);">2</span>
             |  Phase: <span id="liss-ph-disp" style="color:var(--amber);">90°</span>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div>
<div class="controls mb-24">
<div class="control-row">
<span class="control-label">X Frequency</span>
<input id="liss-xfreq" max="8" min="1" oninput="lissUpdate()" step="1" type="range" value="3"/>
<span class="control-value" id="liss-xf-val">3</span>
</div>
<div class="control-row">
<span class="control-label">Y Frequency</span>
<input id="liss-yfreq" max="8" min="1" oninput="lissUpdate()" step="1" type="range" value="2"/>
<span class="control-value" id="liss-yf-val">2</span>
</div>
<div class="control-row">
<span class="control-label">Phase Offset</span>
<input id="liss-phase" max="360" min="0" oninput="lissUpdate()" step="1" type="range" value="90"/>
<span class="control-value" id="liss-ph-val">90°</span>
</div>
</div>
<h4 style="margin-bottom:10px;">Presets</h4>
<div class="btn-row" id="liss-presets" style="flex-wrap:wrap;gap:6px;">
<button class="btn btn-sm" onclick="setLiss(1,1,90)">Circle</button>
<button class="btn btn-sm" onclick="setLiss(1,2,0)">Figure-8</button>
<button class="btn btn-sm active" onclick="setLiss(3,2,90)">Trefoil</button>
<button class="btn btn-sm" onclick="setLiss(3,4,0)">Star</button>
<button class="btn btn-sm" onclick="setLiss(3,5,90)">Butterfly</button>
<button class="btn btn-sm" onclick="setLiss(4,5,0)">Pentagon</button>
</div>
<div class="note-text mt-16">
<strong style="color:var(--green);">Oscilloscope X-Y mode:</strong> two signals fed to horizontal and vertical deflection plates produce geometric forms when their frequency ratio is rational. Jerobeam Fenderson composes music specifically engineered to trace visual sculptures on an oscilloscope screen.
        </div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</section>
<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════
     S04  FM SYNTHESIS
═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="s04">
<div class="section-inner">
<div class="section-header hidden stagger-1">
<div class="section-number">04 / FM SYNTHESIS</div>
<h2>FM Synthesis</h2>
<p class="section-thesis">One oscillator modulates another. The ratio determines everything.</p>
</div>
<div class="two-panel hidden stagger-2" style="align-items:start;gap:40px;">
<!-- LEFT: explanation -->
<div>
<h3>Frequency Modulation</h3>
<p class="info-text mt-16">
        In <span class="highlight">FM synthesis</span>, a <em>modulator</em> oscillator varies the frequency of a <em>carrier</em> oscillator many times per second. The resulting spectrum is rich with <span class="amber-text">sidebands</span> — frequency components above and below the carrier — whose number and amplitude are controlled by the <span class="highlight">modulation index</span>.
      </p>
<p class="info-text mt-16">
        The <strong>carrier:modulator frequency ratio</strong> determines the spectral character. Integer ratios (1:1, 1:2, 1:3) produce <span class="highlight">harmonic</span> timbres — bell-like, piano-like, organ-like. Non-integer ratios produce <span class="amber-text">inharmonic</span> spectra: metallic clang, gongs, industrial textures.
      </p>
<p class="info-text mt-16">
        Yamaha's DX7 (1983) brought FM synthesis to the mainstream. Its six operators, configurable in 32 algorithms, sold over 200,000 units — making the electric piano patch (<span class="highlight">ratio 1:1, index 3.5</span>) one of the most-heard sounds of the 1980s.
      </p>
<div class="note-text mt-16">
<strong style="color:var(--green);">Formula:</strong> output = sin(2π·f_c·t + I·sin(2π·f_m·t)) where f_c = carrier freq, f_m = modulator freq, I = modulation index. As I increases, sidebands multiply exponentially.
      </div>
<div style="margin-top:24px;">
<h4 style="margin-bottom:12px;">Named Presets — click to play</h4>
<div class="btn-row" style="flex-direction:column;gap:8px;align-items:flex-start;">
<button class="btn btn-sm" onclick="playFMPreset(220,1,3.5,'DX7 Electric Piano')">DX7 Electric Piano — ratio 1:1, index 3.5</button>
<button class="btn btn-sm btn-amber" onclick="playFMPreset(280,3.5,5,'Bell')">Bell — ratio 1:3.5, index 5</button>
<button class="btn btn-sm" onclick="playFMPreset(55,2,8,'Bass')">Synth Bass — ratio 2:1, index 8</button>
<button class="btn btn-sm btn-amber" onclick="playFMPreset(440,4,2,'Marimba')">Marimba — ratio 1:4, index 2</button>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<!-- RIGHT: FM grid -->
<div>
<h4 style="margin-bottom:8px;">Ratio × Index Map — click any cell</h4>
<div style="font-family:monospace;font-size:10px;color:var(--text-dim);margin-bottom:12px;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;padding:0 4px;">
<span>← Mod Index 0 ————————————— 10 →</span>
</div>
<div style="display:flex;gap:8px;align-items:center;">
<div style="font-family:monospace;font-size:10px;color:var(--text-dim);writing-mode:vertical-lr;transform:rotate(180deg);letter-spacing:0.1em;white-space:nowrap;">
          ← Ratio 1:1 ——— 1:6 →
        </div>
<canvas class="fm-grid-canvas" height="360" id="fm-grid-canvas" onclick="fmGridClick(event)" style="width:400px;height:360px;border-radius:6px;" width="400"></canvas>
</div>
<div style="margin-top:10px;display:flex;gap:16px;font-family:monospace;font-size:10px;">
